    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-11-07T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-11-07T13:00:00-05:00" n="460"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d460">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">765.84/2296: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Minister in Egypt</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Fish</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-11-07T13:00:00-05:00"
                            >November 7, 1935—1 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>46. Your 88, November 4, 11 a.m. For your strictly confidential information. In
                    view of the policy enunciated in the President’s statement of October 5,
                        1935,<note n="31" xml:id="d460fn31">See telegram No. 11 from the Secretary
                        of State to President Roosevelt, October 5, <ref target="#pg_798">p.
                            798</ref>; the President’s reply October 5, <ref target="#pg_800">p.
                            800</ref>; and telegram to President Roosevelt, October 6, <ref
                            target="#pg_801">p. 801</ref>.</note> the Department is inclined to
                    believe that your mission and the consular offices in Egypt might as a general
                    rule be justified in refraining from intervening on behalf of American nationals
                    who encounter difficulties in Egypt by engaging in trade with Italy or Ethiopia,
                    provided the Egyptian Government does not attempt to invade the rights of such
                    nationals with respect to their immunity from Egyptian jurisdiction. Before
                    adopting any final <pb facs="0693" n="591" xml:id="pg_591"/> attitude in the
                    matter, however, the Department considers it essential to ascertain definitely
                    the form which economic sanctions by Egypt may take and the extent to which they
                    may interfere with American capitulatory rights.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Phillips</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
